Let's fix this by ensuring Maven is using a proper JDK:

1. First, let's update your `pom.xml` to specify a more widely available Java version:

<augment_code_snippet path="pom.xml" mode="EDIT">
```xml
<plugin>
 <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
 <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
 <version>3.11.0</version>
 <configuration>
 <source>17</source>
 <target>17</target>
 </configuration>
</plugin>
```
</augment_code_snippet>

2. Make sure you have a JDK installed. If you're using IntelliJ IDEA, you can check this by going to:
 - File > Project Structure > Project > Project SDK
 - Make sure it points to a JDK, not a JRE

3. Configure Maven to use your JDK by setting the JAVA_HOME environment variable:

<augment_code_snippet path="set-java-home.bat" mode="EDIT">
```batch
@echo off
set JAVA_HOME=C:\path\to\your\jdk
echo JAVA_HOME set to %JAVA_HOME%
```
</augment_code_snippet>

Replace `C:\path\to\your\jdk` with the actual path to your JDK installation.

4. You can also tell Maven explicitly which JDK to use by adding this to your Maven command:

```
mvn clean install -Dmaven.compiler.fork=true -Dmaven.compiler.executable="C:\path\to\your\jdk\bin\javac.exe"
```

5. If you're using IntelliJ IDEA, you can also check:
 - File > Settings > Build, Execution, Deployment > Build Tools > Maven > Runner
 - Make sure "JRE" is set to a valid JDK

After making these changes, try running `mvn clean install` again. This should resolve the compiler issue.
