Looking at the controller code in `AllCaregiverController.java`, the button is connected to the `handleDeactivate()` method:

<augment_code_snippet path="src/main/java/de/hitec/nhplus/controller/AllCaregiverController.java" mode="EXCERPT">
```java
this.btnDelete.setOnAction(event -> handleDeactivate());

@FXML
public void handleDeactivate() {
 Caregiver selectedItem = this.tableView.getSelectionModel().getSelectedItem();
 if (selectedItem != null) {
 try {
 selectedItem.setActive(false);
 this.dao.update(selectedItem);
 readAllAndShowInTableView();
 } catch (SQLException e) {
 e.printStackTrace();
 }
 } else {
 showNoSelectionAlert();
 }
}
```
</augment_code_snippet>

When clicked, the button:
1. Gets the currently selected caregiver from the table
2. Sets their `active` status to `false`
3. Updates the caregiver record in the database
4. Refreshes the table view to reflect the changes

This approach is consistent with how deletion is handled in other parts of the application, like the `UserDao` which also performs soft deletes by setting `is_active` to 0 rather than removing records completely.
